WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
www.osdb.link/lm

2
00:00:16.057 --> 00:00:19.436
Pa says the most important thing
about digging a well is

3
00:00:19.519 --> 00:00:20.812
to mind the bad air.

4
00:00:21.354 --> 00:00:26.026
You can't see it. can't smell it.
but it can kill you if you're not careful.

5
00:00:27.694 --> 00:00:31.406
Every morning. before they begin.
they send the candle down.

6
00:00:31.906 --> 00:00:34.367
If the flame goes out. no one goes in.

7
00:00:34.868 --> 00:00:36.244
Those are the rules.

8
00:00:43.418 --> 00:00:44.586
Let's get to work.

9
00:00:52.594 --> 00:00:53.595
Rope.

10
00:01:22.707 --> 00:01:25.376
Morning. Mr. and Mrs. Ingalls!
Don't mind me.

11
00:01:25.877 --> 00:01:27.462
Thought I'd get an early start.

12
00:01:37.347 --> 00:01:39.766
You can't blame a young man
for his enthusiasm.

13
00:01:39.849 --> 00:01:42.435
You rest. I'll put on the coffee.

14
00:02:00.036 --> 00:02:01.371
I got the coffee.

15
00:02:02.080 --> 00:02:05.333
I told Caroline to sleep in.
so I can't guarantee it'll taste any good.

16
00:02:05.834 --> 00:02:07.460
It will get the job done.

17
00:02:08.586 --> 00:02:09.420
Adam?

18
00:02:15.135 --> 00:02:16.135
Adam?

19
00:02:16.594 --> 00:02:19.889
Caroline! Caroline!

20
00:02:53.464 --> 00:02:56.301
What happened?

21
00:03:05.727 --> 00:03:07.687
Caroline! Hold on!

22
00:03:15.653 --> 00:03:19.199
Adam! Adam! Adam! Adam!

23
00:03:19.282 --> 00:03:21.951
-Is he dead?
-Adam. Hey. Adam.

24
00:03:23.703 --> 00:03:26.998
Did you put the candle down first?
What did I say. George?

25
00:03:27.081 --> 00:03:29.500
-What did I say about the rules?
-Hey.

26
00:03:31.794 --> 00:03:33.254
I'm sorry. Mr. Ingalls.

27
00:03:55.985 --> 00:03:57.237
Are you nervous?

28
00:03:58.696 --> 00:04:00.281
About the Women's Society?

29
00:04:01.282 --> 00:04:02.282
No.

30
00:04:05.036 --> 00:04:06.120
Maybe a little.

31
00:04:07.956 --> 00:04:08.957
What about you?

32
00:04:09.666 --> 00:04:13.878
No. I am dying to meet the James girls.

33
00:04:14.587 --> 00:04:17.215
Maybe they like Dickens or Hawthorne.

34
00:04:17.298 --> 00:04:20.301
Maybe they have books
I can borrow to read to the new baby.

35
00:04:20.385 --> 00:04:24.347
I wanna know what samplers they've done
and what poems they know.

36
00:04:27.517 --> 00:04:30.311
Do you think I look like someone that
they'd wanna be friends with?

37
00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:33.606
Absolutely.

38
00:04:39.487 --> 00:04:41.823
Laura. you're next.

39
00:04:53.084 --> 00:04:54.460
I miss Pet and Patty.

40
00:04:56.129 --> 00:04:57.129
Me too.

41
00:04:57.714 --> 00:04:59.632
I thought they'd be back by now.

42
00:05:00.258 --> 00:05:02.778
Lots of people's horses
went missing during the fever.

43
00:05:03.219 --> 00:05:05.763
Had nothing to do with you. Promise.

44
00:05:07.348 --> 00:05:09.183
Can I help you build the church today?

45
00:05:10.059 --> 00:05:13.396
I could carry your tools
or get water or hold nails.

46
00:05:13.479 --> 00:05:16.816
-I promise I won't get in the way.
-You have plans with the James girls.

47
00:05:17.483 --> 00:05:19.569
Town girls never like me.

48
00:05:20.862 --> 00:05:22.322
They always like Mary.

49
00:05:24.115 --> 00:05:28.286
All you have to do is be yourself.
and it will be impossible not to like you.

50
00:05:29.620 --> 00:05:30.913
Hair. please.

51
00:05:35.376 --> 00:05:38.254
Let's get this wilderness
looking respectable.

52
00:05:44.510 --> 00:05:46.512
How's Mad Dog look?

53
00:05:46.596 --> 00:05:47.764
Respectable?

54
00:05:57.565 --> 00:05:59.817
I want you to be
on your best behavior today.

55
00:05:59.901 --> 00:06:01.652
Mrs. James is very important.

56
00:06:01.736 --> 00:06:05.156
We want her to know we're ready to step up
and be a part of the community here.

57
00:06:05.948 --> 00:06:08.159
-All of us.
-Yes. Ma.

58
00:06:09.118 --> 00:06:10.912
Make pleasant conversation.

59
00:06:10.995 --> 00:06:13.873
compliment your hosts. and no arguing.

60
00:06:13.956 --> 00:06:15.708
-Do you understand?
-Yes. Ma.

61
00:06:17.960 --> 00:06:20.922
Guests are polite. agreeable.
and gracious. okay?

62
00:06:21.005 --> 00:06:24.217
Please and thank yous.
Small bites. no second helpings.

63
00:06:24.717 --> 00:06:26.928
-Make a good impression.
-Yes. Ma.

64
00:06:28.471 --> 00:06:31.557
If we wanted to make a good impression.
we should've left you at home.

65
00:06:32.141 --> 00:06:35.978
You're just scared they'll like me better.
I bet you they will.

66
00:06:36.062 --> 00:06:37.647
Fine. it's a bet.

67
00:06:39.273 --> 00:06:41.234
Ingalls! Impeccable timing.

68
00:06:42.068 --> 00:06:45.113
-I've got your plans right here.
-You remember my wife. Caroline.

69
00:06:45.196 --> 00:06:47.907
-Our daughters. Mary and Laura.
-Of course. What a pleasure.

70
00:06:47.990 --> 00:06:52.662
-You have a very lovely home. Mr. James.
-Yes. it's very lovely. Mr. James.

71
00:06:52.745 --> 00:06:56.958
That's very kind of you to say so.
Go on in. Make yourselves at home.

72
00:06:57.041 --> 00:06:59.669
Jemma and the twins are expecting you.

73
00:07:00.169 --> 00:07:02.755
Charles and I are off to build a church.

74
00:07:02.839 --> 00:07:04.424
-Wish us luck.
-Good luck.

75
00:07:07.593 --> 00:07:09.429
-Save me a cookie.
-Yes. Pa.

76
00:07:13.307 --> 00:07:14.517
Beautiful family.

77
00:07:19.897 --> 00:07:22.733
Caroline! Girls!

78
00:07:22.817 --> 00:07:24.527
Thank you for the invitation.

79
00:07:24.610 --> 00:07:28.281
-I… I brought some blackberry jam.
-How clever you are.

80
00:07:28.364 --> 00:07:30.575
Could you please
put these out with the scones?

81
00:07:31.159 --> 00:07:33.161
Girls. come. please!

82
00:07:33.244 --> 00:07:36.456
-These are for you. Mrs. James.
-Sweet girl.

83
00:07:37.707 --> 00:07:41.335
Mary. Laura. I'd like you
to meet my twins. Romanzy and Edith.

84
00:07:41.419 --> 00:07:42.545
Do you wanna see our room?

85
00:07:44.964 --> 00:07:45.965
That would be lovely.

86
00:07:47.508 --> 00:07:49.093
Yes. lovely.

87
00:07:53.514 --> 00:07:55.114
I can't wait for you to meet the others.

88
00:07:55.183 --> 00:07:57.935
I've been telling them
absolutely everything about you.

89
00:07:58.019 --> 00:08:00.021
-All good. I hope.
-Of course.

90
00:08:00.104 --> 00:08:04.650
We're two peas in a pod. aren't we?
I think we'll make a wonderful team.

91
00:08:04.734 --> 00:08:06.861
I'm sure we will.

92
00:08:07.862 --> 00:08:10.281
I guess you'll be looking
for a new pair.

93
00:08:10.364 --> 00:08:13.451
I'm not quite ready to give up on 'em yet.
Pet and Patty are like family.

94
00:08:13.534 --> 00:08:14.368
Hm.

95
00:08:14.452 --> 00:08:17.497
Well. a man's horse
is an extension of himself.

96
00:08:17.580 --> 00:08:20.166
They might as well have stolen
an arm or a leg.

97
00:08:21.417 --> 00:08:24.837
I should've known Independence
would attract horse thieves.

98
00:08:25.671 --> 00:08:28.925
Unfortunately. where there are men.
there is crime.

99
00:08:30.009 --> 00:08:32.845
I thought maybe they'd moved on.
but just yesterday.

100
00:08:32.929 --> 00:08:36.265
Russell Kind had one of his
stolen out from under him.

101
00:08:36.891 --> 00:08:39.727
Just another reminder
that as our town expands.

102
00:08:39.810 --> 00:08:42.146
so do our needs for law and order.

103
00:08:42.897 --> 00:08:45.525
which is why I've sent for
a federal marshal.

104
00:08:45.608 --> 00:08:47.693
We need rules. Charles.

105
00:08:48.194 --> 00:08:50.821
Rules are what make a society run.

106
00:08:52.031 --> 00:08:54.158
-Morning. gentlemen.
-Good morning.

107
00:08:55.785 --> 00:08:57.578
-How are you feeling?
-Fine.

108
00:08:57.662 --> 00:08:58.871
And I promise.

109
00:08:59.705 --> 00:09:01.065
I'll never make the mistake again.

110
00:09:02.124 --> 00:09:02.959
Glad to hear it.

111
00:09:03.042 --> 00:09:05.253
He's been telling the tale
of how the great hero.

112
00:09:05.336 --> 00:09:08.005
Charles Ingalls.
saved his life to anyone with ears.

113
00:09:12.510 --> 00:09:14.595
Gentlemen. may I have
your attention. please?

114
00:09:14.679 --> 00:09:15.972
Before we begin.

115
00:09:16.055 --> 00:09:18.182
I'd like to thank Charles Ingalls

116
00:09:18.266 --> 00:09:21.310
for drafting such a vision
for this church.

117
00:09:21.394 --> 00:09:22.937
-Hear. hear.
-Hear. hear.

118
00:09:23.563 --> 00:09:24.981
Thank you. Mr. Ingalls.

119
00:09:25.064 --> 00:09:29.402
When I first stepped foot on this land.
I… I felt something.

120
00:09:30.653 --> 00:09:34.615
I felt inspired. I felt at peace.

121
00:09:34.699 --> 00:09:36.325
But most of all.

122
00:09:36.826 --> 00:09:38.202
I felt the Lord.

123
00:09:39.287 --> 00:09:42.748
Let's give this town a place to worship!

124
00:09:42.832 --> 00:09:44.625
-Hear. hear.
-Hear. hear.

125
00:09:44.709 --> 00:09:45.918
Let's get to work.

126
00:09:47.461 --> 00:09:48.461
Hi.

127
00:09:49.880 --> 00:09:51.640
But he won't sit still.

128
00:09:52.466 --> 00:09:53.509
Caroline.

129
00:09:53.593 --> 00:09:57.930
I'd like you to meet Margaret Parker.
whose husband owns the mill.

130
00:09:58.014 --> 00:10:00.266
Sarah Graves.
younger sister of Clarence Graves.

131
00:10:00.349 --> 00:10:02.351
who owns the Independence Pioneer.

132
00:10:02.435 --> 00:10:04.020
and Winnie Richardson.

133
00:10:04.103 --> 00:10:06.105
Her husband has an import business.

134
00:10:06.188 --> 00:10:09.859
Ladies. Caroline Ingalls
is the teacher I told you about.

135
00:10:09.942 --> 00:10:11.235
It's a pleasure.

136
00:10:11.319 --> 00:10:13.946
Your husband designed
the church being built. correct?

137
00:10:14.030 --> 00:10:15.990
-Mm.
-Oh. you must be so proud.

138
00:10:16.073 --> 00:10:17.116
I am. Hm.

139
00:10:17.199 --> 00:10:20.870
I was thinking we might even use
that church as a school in the spring.

140
00:10:20.953 --> 00:10:21.996
Oh yes.

141
00:10:22.079 --> 00:10:26.459
I can't tell you how excited I was to hear
we have an experienced teacher amongst us.

142
00:10:26.542 --> 00:10:27.877
I'm a little out of practice.

143
00:10:27.960 --> 00:10:30.546
but I'm teaching the girls
lessons at home right now.

144
00:10:30.630 --> 00:10:33.049
Oh. her girls are darling. And smart.

145
00:10:33.132 --> 00:10:36.344
Well. if Jemma invited you.
you must be worth your weight in gold.

146
00:10:36.427 --> 00:10:38.888
-I think so.
-Are you taking on students?

147
00:10:38.971 --> 00:10:41.223
Because I'm hopeless
with sums and grammar.

148
00:10:41.307 --> 00:10:43.309
and my boys are driving me absolutely mad.

149
00:10:43.392 --> 00:10:44.435
Oh…

150
00:10:44.518 --> 00:10:47.480
-Oh. I don't know.
-Please. won't you consider it?

151
00:10:47.563 --> 00:10:50.232
Jemma said you've already got
at least one extra student.

152
00:10:50.316 --> 00:10:53.861
Didn't you mention that? A neighbor girl?
I'm not sure you said who though.

153
00:10:53.944 --> 00:10:54.945
Oh…

154
00:10:55.446 --> 00:10:56.947
It's nothing formal.

155
00:10:57.448 --> 00:11:01.077
I have two at home that haven't been
to school in over a year.

156
00:11:01.160 --> 00:11:04.163
It seems you have a lot to discuss.
I'll leave you to it.

157
00:11:09.794 --> 00:11:13.839
-Where did you get all these clothes?
-Mother's always had a trunk for dress-up.

158
00:11:13.923 --> 00:11:17.426
She says it simulates a sense
of fashion and sophistication.

159
00:11:17.510 --> 00:11:21.722
I'll be Lady Francesca of Yomesford.
the secret heiress to the throne.

160
00:11:21.806 --> 00:11:24.725
You two can be Eleanor and Catherine.

161
00:11:24.809 --> 00:11:28.396
my trusted loyals.
sworn to protect my secret at all costs.

162
00:11:28.479 --> 00:11:29.855
Now. go on. Pick something.

163
00:11:36.987 --> 00:11:37.822
Ooh!

164
00:11:37.905 --> 00:11:39.615
-Elegant.
-Thank you.

165
00:11:39.699 --> 00:11:41.033
Now you. Laura.

166
00:11:53.295 --> 00:11:54.547
Um. not that one.

167
00:11:55.047 --> 00:11:56.767
-But you said...
-That one's mine.

168
00:11:56.841 --> 00:11:59.468
Father bought it for me
from an honest-to-goodness cowboy.

169
00:12:01.262 --> 00:12:02.382
I like your necklace.

170
00:12:02.430 --> 00:12:04.724
Father brought this
from New York for my birthday.

171
00:12:04.807 --> 00:12:08.686
He said it was from England and possibly
belonged to Queen Victoria herself.

172
00:12:10.312 --> 00:12:11.981
It's very sophisticated.

173
00:12:12.773 --> 00:12:15.401
and perfect for high tea
with Lady Francesca.

174
00:12:15.901 --> 00:12:18.446
What did your father
give you for your last birthday?

175
00:12:18.529 --> 00:12:20.948
He made me a slingshot out of sugar maple.

176
00:12:21.741 --> 00:12:22.741
A slingshot?

177
00:12:23.117 --> 00:12:25.077
I can get a rabbit from 20 paces.

178
00:12:25.161 --> 00:12:27.121
Get? You mean kill?

179
00:12:27.204 --> 00:12:28.664
It makes a good stew.

180
00:12:29.415 --> 00:12:32.251
Lady Francesca.
please forgive my sister's poor taste.

181
00:12:32.835 --> 00:12:35.087
You. however. look simply marvelous.

182
00:12:35.171 --> 00:12:37.214
The duke is a very lucky man.

183
00:12:37.298 --> 00:12:38.424
He is. isn't he?

184
00:12:41.594 --> 00:12:44.930
That hat looks absolutely
delicious on you. Eleanor.

185
00:12:45.431 --> 00:12:48.017
Let me see if we can find you
some lace gloves too.

186
00:12:51.812 --> 00:12:53.773
Do you prefer pink or white?

187
00:12:56.776 --> 00:12:59.820
Ready. heave!

188
00:12:59.904 --> 00:13:02.448
Ready. heave!

189
00:13:04.450 --> 00:13:06.827
Ready. heave!

190
00:13:09.663 --> 00:13:12.291
Heave!

191
00:13:12.374 --> 00:13:15.294
Ready. heave!

192
00:13:15.878 --> 00:13:18.047
Ready. heave!

193
00:13:19.882 --> 00:13:25.304
Ready. heave! Ready. heave!

194
00:13:26.639 --> 00:13:28.516
Hold. hold. hold. hold. hold!

195
00:13:46.200 --> 00:13:48.869
-Thought I'd stop by. say hello.
-Good to see you.

196
00:13:49.703 --> 00:13:53.207
My. uh. translating job kept me away
longer than I was expecting.

197
00:13:54.667 --> 00:13:58.462
Thank you for looking in on
my family during the fever.

198
00:13:58.546 --> 00:14:00.965
I can't take credit. I was sick as a dog.

199
00:14:01.048 --> 00:14:04.218
-It was all Laura.
-That's what my daughter keeps telling me.

200
00:14:06.136 --> 00:14:09.849
-How was your trip?
-I met the new Indian agent. Isaac Gibson.

201
00:14:10.349 --> 00:14:12.518
-He's a Quaker.
-How'd it go?

202
00:14:12.601 --> 00:14:13.601
I'm not sure yet.

203
00:14:14.228 --> 00:14:17.982
But he seems set on putting
a removal agreement in place

204
00:14:18.065 --> 00:14:19.400
as soon as possible.

205
00:14:20.276 --> 00:14:21.652
A removal agreement?

206
00:14:21.735 --> 00:14:23.237
A deal for the land.

207
00:14:27.032 --> 00:14:28.909
A fair one. I hope.

208
00:14:29.410 --> 00:14:33.247
Seven chiefs have to agree to the terms.
There's still a lot to be discussed.

209
00:14:34.415 --> 00:14:37.918
We're probably looking at spring
before anything would get signed.

210
00:14:41.672 --> 00:14:43.173
Is it all right if I call lunch?

211
00:14:43.966 --> 00:14:46.677
-The honor's all yours.
-Stay and eat with us. Mr. Mitchell?

212
00:14:46.760 --> 00:14:49.221
I brought lots to share.
It's an old habit.

213
00:14:49.305 --> 00:14:50.825
Nobody much liked me when I was young.

214
00:14:50.890 --> 00:14:53.642
so I'd stuff my bag full
of treats to hand out at lunch.

215
00:14:54.143 --> 00:14:57.187
-It always worked.
-Thank you. I'll do it.

216
00:15:00.649 --> 00:15:01.984
That's lunch. gentlemen!

217
00:15:02.484 --> 00:15:06.030
Mother says Adam Scott is
from a family of bankers in Boston.

218
00:15:06.113 --> 00:15:07.698
She says they are very wealthy.

219
00:15:07.781 --> 00:15:11.285
But even so. his fiancée
left him standing at the altar.

220
00:15:11.368 --> 00:15:14.079
-It was quite the scandal.
-That's so sad to hear.

221
00:15:14.663 --> 00:15:15.664
Poor Adam.

222
00:15:15.748 --> 00:15:17.588
You mean rich Adam.

223
00:15:17.666 --> 00:15:21.003
Now he's the most
eligible bachelor in Independence.

224
00:15:21.086 --> 00:15:23.839
Mother says he'll find a wife any day now.
He's got a trust fund.

225
00:15:23.923 --> 00:15:26.091
He is very good-looking.

226
00:15:26.175 --> 00:15:28.594
He… he is. isn't he?

227
00:15:29.595 --> 00:15:33.015
-What do you think. Laura?
-About what?

228
00:15:33.098 --> 00:15:34.266
Adam.

229
00:15:35.684 --> 00:15:37.353
He almost died in our well.

230
00:15:39.104 --> 00:15:40.272
Laura!

231
00:15:40.856 --> 00:15:44.360
Don't be gruesome.
Please forgive my sister her manners.

232
00:15:49.865 --> 00:15:51.283
May I be excused?

233
00:15:51.992 --> 00:15:53.035
You're excused.

234
00:15:57.748 --> 00:16:00.793
Mary. do you think
any other boys in town are cute?

235
00:16:02.211 --> 00:16:04.213
You do! Who?

236
00:16:05.839 --> 00:16:07.174
Do you know Caleb?

237
00:16:07.257 --> 00:16:12.304
Caleb? That chowderhead orphan boy
who works at the General Store?

238
00:16:14.181 --> 00:16:15.808
Oh! No.

239
00:16:16.433 --> 00:16:20.813
I was thinking of a boy who lives
a few homesteads away from us.

240
00:16:21.689 --> 00:16:25.109
I thought his name was Caleb.
It must be Jacob.

241
00:16:25.609 --> 00:16:29.071
You know. Caleb's parents
left him out on the trail.

242
00:16:29.154 --> 00:16:32.783
Just up and walked away in the middle
of the night and left him on his own.

243
00:16:33.367 --> 00:16:34.743
Why would they do that?

244
00:16:34.827 --> 00:16:37.955
-Maybe they didn't want him.
-Or maybe they were eaten by wolves.

245
00:16:38.038 --> 00:16:39.999
Or maybe there's something wrong with him.

246
00:16:40.082 --> 00:16:42.001
Maybe he drove them away.

247
00:16:47.548 --> 00:16:50.884
Now that the church is on its way.
I wonder if we should bring in a reverend?

248
00:16:50.968 --> 00:16:51.844
-Mmm.
-Mmm.

249
00:16:51.927 --> 00:16:55.389
I'm a long way from home. but I'm sure
one of you have connections in the area.

250
00:16:55.472 --> 00:16:58.183
I know an excellent candidate
from Elk City. Walter Eaton.

251
00:16:58.267 --> 00:17:01.020
He's been traveling the state
helping set up funds for the poor.

252
00:17:01.103 --> 00:17:03.230
but I know he'd love
to settle down for a spell.

253
00:17:03.313 --> 00:17:07.026
Well. I've already taken the liberty
of arranging for Reverend Daniel Franklin

254
00:17:07.109 --> 00:17:08.318
from St. Louis.

255
00:17:08.819 --> 00:17:12.072
Oh. he's a man of extraordinary faith
and character.

256
00:17:12.156 --> 00:17:15.534
And he comes from one of the most
respected families in the city.

257
00:17:15.617 --> 00:17:17.971
St. Louis is a long way to come.

258
00:17:17.995 --> 00:17:21.707
It's important to have not just someone.
but the right someone.

259
00:17:21.790 --> 00:17:23.667
I'm sure Caroline would agree.

260
00:17:28.047 --> 00:17:29.089
Of course.

261
00:17:30.007 --> 00:17:31.007
Hm.

262
00:17:34.053 --> 00:17:34.887
When you're ready.

263
00:17:36.805 --> 00:17:38.557
-Do it.
-On three.

264
00:17:39.058 --> 00:17:40.100
One…

265
00:17:40.184 --> 00:17:41.643
There you go.

266
00:17:47.399 --> 00:17:50.861
-What has my brother done now?
-He lost his footing and he landed wrong.

267
00:17:52.071 --> 00:17:53.363
He'll be just fine though.

268
00:17:53.447 --> 00:17:56.784
Might wanna have Caleb do
the heavy lifting for a couple of weeks.

269
00:17:56.867 --> 00:17:58.547
You were supposed to come back an hour ago

270
00:17:58.577 --> 00:18:00.337
so I could go
to the Women's Society meeting.

271
00:18:00.370 --> 00:18:02.081
I guess I lost track of time.

272
00:18:02.164 --> 00:18:03.332
I guess you did.

273
00:18:03.832 --> 00:18:05.709
I'll be on my way. then.

274
00:18:05.793 --> 00:18:07.795
Thank you. Dr. Tann.

275
00:18:08.545 --> 00:18:09.545
Yeah.

276
00:18:15.594 --> 00:18:19.223
I made cookies. Building a church
calls for a treat. I'd say.

277
00:18:23.310 --> 00:18:25.604
-Gingersnaps are my favorite.
-I know.

278
00:18:29.775 --> 00:18:31.443
I don't wanna keep you from your meeting.

279
00:18:31.527 --> 00:18:34.154
I never mind
an extra moment or two with you. doctor.

280
00:18:36.323 --> 00:18:38.492
Now. have a good day. Be safe.

281
00:19:08.021 --> 00:19:09.061
Hm.

282
00:19:09.106 --> 00:19:11.483
I apologize for my late arrival.

283
00:19:15.195 --> 00:19:16.321
I brought cookies.

284
00:19:16.822 --> 00:19:18.991
I… I see.

285
00:19:22.411 --> 00:19:24.538
The Women's Society is today. isn't it?

286
00:19:24.621 --> 00:19:27.875
I feel like I've been staring
at that flyer in my store for weeks.

287
00:19:27.958 --> 00:19:32.880
Oh. I'm afraid the Women's Society is
for the married women of Independence.

288
00:19:34.131 --> 00:19:35.215
The married women?

289
00:19:36.550 --> 00:19:37.676
-That's right.
-Mmm.

290
00:19:38.719 --> 00:19:39.803
It's protocol.

291
00:19:40.304 --> 00:19:41.847
I'm sure you understand.

292
00:19:43.765 --> 00:19:44.933
I'm sure I do.

293
00:19:47.144 --> 00:19:49.605
My apologies for the misunderstanding.

294
00:19:58.030 --> 00:20:00.157
Did you hear
how Mr. Ingalls saved my life?

295
00:20:00.657 --> 00:20:02.701
I was just about dead
at the bottom of a well.

296
00:20:02.784 --> 00:20:04.328
and he jumped in to pull me out.

297
00:20:04.912 --> 00:20:06.079
Everybody's heard.

298
00:20:06.872 --> 00:20:10.959
I don't mind if people make fun. I'm just
grateful to be alive. He's a hero.

299
00:20:11.877 --> 00:20:13.003
It's true.

300
00:20:13.086 --> 00:20:15.547
What about in the war. Mr. Ingalls?
Where'd you fight?

301
00:20:16.506 --> 00:20:18.342
I'll bet you were a real hero there too.

302
00:20:18.425 --> 00:20:21.553
I wanted to sign up.
but Grandfather said I was too young.

303
00:20:24.848 --> 00:20:28.143
My father needed my help.
I stayed back to work the farms with him.

304
00:20:29.019 --> 00:20:30.103
Oh.

305
00:20:30.938 --> 00:20:32.606
I didn't know you could do that.

306
00:20:33.565 --> 00:20:34.565
You can't.

307
00:20:35.692 --> 00:20:37.986
I guess some people don't think
the rules apply to them.

308
00:20:46.578 --> 00:20:47.913
I got the horse thief.

309
00:20:51.583 --> 00:20:53.085
What's all this. Russell?

310
00:20:53.710 --> 00:20:56.672
Well. while you were sitting on your ass.

311
00:20:57.214 --> 00:20:59.174
we tracked this degenerate down.

312
00:21:10.394 --> 00:21:13.981
-Edwards isn't a thief. and you know it.
-I don't know any such thing.

313
00:21:14.064 --> 00:21:16.233
I told you to leave this
with me. Kind.

314
00:21:16.316 --> 00:21:19.111
You're not the law here.
and you don't have any proof.

315
00:21:19.194 --> 00:21:22.781
He's been roaming the prairie
in the dead of night for weeks.

316
00:21:22.864 --> 00:21:25.450
scoping us out. lying in wait.

317
00:21:25.534 --> 00:21:28.662
-We've all seen him.
-That's true. I've seen him.

318
00:21:28.745 --> 00:21:30.747
And as soon as
the horses go missing.

319
00:21:30.831 --> 00:21:33.750
well. all of a sudden
he's waving around stacks of cash.

320
00:21:33.834 --> 00:21:37.754
His whiskey business busted up.
so he went straight for the horses.

321
00:21:37.838 --> 00:21:40.007
just like he did back in Tennessee.

322
00:21:40.090 --> 00:21:41.967
Go ahead. ask him.

323
00:21:42.050 --> 00:21:43.385
He won't deny it.

324
00:21:43.468 --> 00:21:45.721
Edwards. say something.

325
00:21:47.306 --> 00:21:48.807
Untie him!

326
00:21:49.683 --> 00:21:53.478
Untie him. you disgusting little toad!

327
00:21:53.562 --> 00:21:56.064
The only money
he's waving around is yours.

328
00:21:56.148 --> 00:21:58.692
after he took you
for everything you're worth in cards.

329
00:22:00.569 --> 00:22:02.029
And you too. Bronson.

330
00:22:03.196 --> 00:22:06.700
Or should I ask your wife about it?
All the money you lost at my place?

331
00:22:06.783 --> 00:22:08.160
Stay out of it.

332
00:22:09.202 --> 00:22:12.164
Last time I'm gonna say it. Untie him now.

333
00:22:13.123 --> 00:22:14.291
Lacey!

334
00:22:14.374 --> 00:22:16.168
I'm not letting him
get thrown to the wolves.

335
00:22:16.251 --> 00:22:19.546
There's not gonna be
any frontier justice on my watch.

336
00:22:19.629 --> 00:22:22.215
Until the marshal arrives
to sort this out.

337
00:22:22.299 --> 00:22:24.426
we'll hold Mr. Edwards at the hotel.

338
00:22:26.053 --> 00:22:27.053
Come on.

339
00:22:28.347 --> 00:22:30.223
It's for your own safety.

340
00:22:37.022 --> 00:22:38.023
Lacey.

341
00:22:39.399 --> 00:22:41.818
-Where are you going?
-To clear his name.

342
00:22:42.319 --> 00:22:44.321
You really think Eli is gonna stop Kind

343
00:22:44.404 --> 00:22:46.531
and his idiots
from doing something stupid?

344
00:22:46.615 --> 00:22:49.242
You can ride out to see
the Osage with me if you want to.

345
00:22:49.326 --> 00:22:52.954
Or you can stay here and be Eli's puppet.

346
00:22:54.247 --> 00:22:57.125
-The Osage didn't do this.
-I didn't say that they did.

347
00:22:57.209 --> 00:22:59.795
But nothing gets past
that brother-in-law of yours.

348
00:22:59.878 --> 00:23:01.922
I got him out of a scrape last month.
He owes me.

349
00:23:02.005 --> 00:23:03.924
I'm not gonna let her ride out on her own.

350
00:23:04.007 --> 00:23:06.426
You can take my horse.
I'll go keep an eye on Edwards.

351
00:23:27.030 --> 00:23:31.618
Now that lunch is out of the way.
we should probably get down to business.

352
00:23:32.327 --> 00:23:35.831
Will you sit with me up front?
Perhaps jot down a few notes?

353
00:23:36.623 --> 00:23:38.708
Do you mind if I run and get Emily
before we start?

354
00:23:38.792 --> 00:23:40.152
I don't want her to miss anything.

355
00:23:40.210 --> 00:23:43.463
She must've lost track of time.
I'll be fast. I promise.

356
00:23:43.547 --> 00:23:46.049
Oh. that's why she had the idea to come.

357
00:23:47.717 --> 00:23:48.844
She was here?

358
00:23:48.927 --> 00:23:49.761
Yes.

359
00:23:49.845 --> 00:23:53.807
And as I explained to her.
the society is for married women.

360
00:23:53.890 --> 00:23:57.144
Of course. I apologized
profusely for the inconvenience.

361
00:23:57.227 --> 00:23:58.437
I'm not married.

362
00:24:00.230 --> 00:24:04.443
Yes. but you're a writer
and from a very respectable family.

363
00:24:04.526 --> 00:24:07.988
What's not respectable about running
the largest store in Independence?

364
00:24:09.072 --> 00:24:11.825
This society has rules. Caroline.

365
00:24:12.409 --> 00:24:14.870
Now. ladies. if you'll find your seats.

366
00:24:14.953 --> 00:24:18.331
I thought we could start
our discussion with the vote.

367
00:24:18.415 --> 00:24:21.835
Women account for
over half the population of this country.

368
00:24:21.918 --> 00:24:25.464
and yet we are unable to participate
in deciding its direction.

369
00:24:26.256 --> 00:24:28.717
I think it's time we change that.

370
00:24:28.800 --> 00:24:31.094
starting with Independence.

371
00:24:34.014 --> 00:24:35.098
Caroline.

372
00:24:44.774 --> 00:24:45.984
Now. vote.

373
00:24:46.067 --> 00:24:47.777
Vote begins with V.

374
00:24:47.861 --> 00:24:49.779
What else begins with V? Voice.

375
00:25:03.835 --> 00:25:06.671
What are you doing? Those are
from Father's special collection.

376
00:25:06.755 --> 00:25:08.215
and we're not supposed to open them.

377
00:25:08.882 --> 00:25:09.716
Why?

378
00:25:09.799 --> 00:25:12.636
Because it's not proper
to look at drawings of half-naked men.

379
00:25:12.719 --> 00:25:15.055
But that's just how they dress.

380
00:25:15.847 --> 00:25:19.184
Everything they wear has a meaning.
even the colors.

381
00:25:19.684 --> 00:25:20.684
See?

382
00:25:22.187 --> 00:25:23.187
Laura.

383
00:25:24.689 --> 00:25:25.982
put it back.

384
00:25:27.943 --> 00:25:29.903
I'm sorry. My sister's a wilding.

385
00:25:35.742 --> 00:25:37.160
My best friend is Osage.

386
00:25:38.245 --> 00:25:39.621
Her name is Good Eagle.

387
00:25:40.288 --> 00:25:42.207
Indians have come
to your house?

388
00:25:42.290 --> 00:25:43.667
Of course.

389
00:25:44.167 --> 00:25:45.502
And not just Good Eagle.

390
00:25:47.504 --> 00:25:48.964
Do you wanna hear a story?

391
00:25:55.428 --> 00:25:59.182
One morning. when Pa was off
helping Mr. Scott build his house.

392
00:25:59.266 --> 00:26:02.060
Jack and I came home from the creek

393
00:26:02.143 --> 00:26:06.273
to find unexpected visitors.

394
00:26:10.652 --> 00:26:12.946
I already told you.

395
00:26:13.029 --> 00:26:15.824
I didn't take the horses.

396
00:26:16.950 --> 00:26:19.119
You hear that?
I didn't take your horses.

397
00:26:19.202 --> 00:26:23.373
I didn't say you took them.

398
00:26:23.957 --> 00:26:26.459
I'm guessing you know a place or two

399
00:26:26.543 --> 00:26:30.046
where a dozen could be hidden
without drawing attention.

400
00:26:30.547 --> 00:26:35.385
Let your squatter friends
figure it out for themselves.

401
00:26:38.221 --> 00:26:40.932
If they can hunt our game.

402
00:26:41.016 --> 00:26:44.019
they can hunt for their own horses.

403
00:26:44.102 --> 00:26:50.358
Louis lost a horse last week.

404
00:26:51.192 --> 00:26:55.113
How long before you start
missing horses too?

405
00:27:01.328 --> 00:27:03.580
Fine. I'll show you.

406
00:27:25.477 --> 00:27:27.479
Thought I'd take a look at that bruise.

407
00:27:29.564 --> 00:27:31.858
-That'd be all right?
-I'm fine.

408
00:27:59.260 --> 00:28:01.930
I don't understand
why you didn't stand up for yourself.

409
00:28:02.430 --> 00:28:05.517
You're a lot of things. John.
but you're not a thief.

410
00:28:08.770 --> 00:28:10.814
We can talk. or we can just sit.

411
00:28:19.072 --> 00:28:22.283
I spent the past few weeks
drying out on Lacey's porch.

412
00:28:24.369 --> 00:28:26.663
Sobering up's supposed to be
a good thing. but

413
00:28:28.289 --> 00:28:31.751
nobody tells you about all the hours
you're forced to sit with your thoughts.

414
00:28:36.673 --> 00:28:40.009
Today is six years since I came home
and found all my girls gone.

415
00:28:41.928 --> 00:28:42.928
Cholera.

416
00:28:45.640 --> 00:28:48.435
And every day since
has been like a knife in my heart.

417
00:28:50.687 --> 00:28:51.771
And for what?

418
00:28:54.774 --> 00:28:57.777
What did I get in return
for choosing war over my family?

419
00:29:00.739 --> 00:29:03.366
Kind came for me.
I thought. well. maybe this is it.

420
00:29:03.450 --> 00:29:06.286
Maybe I'll finally get to be
with my girls again.

421
00:29:08.246 --> 00:29:11.750
War took a piece of every man
and woman in this country.

422
00:29:14.210 --> 00:29:16.337
And even though the cause was just.

423
00:29:17.922 --> 00:29:21.050
everyone lost something
they can't get back.

424
00:29:24.471 --> 00:29:28.600
All I know is there are people
in this town who care about you.

425
00:29:30.101 --> 00:29:32.020
Maybe start letting 'em do that.

426
00:29:33.730 --> 00:29:35.982
Maybe you start thinking about a future.

427
00:29:59.130 --> 00:30:00.632
There's my Pet and Patty.

428
00:30:00.715 --> 00:30:01.883
See?

429
00:30:01.966 --> 00:30:05.094
And those are Osage horses.

430
00:30:05.845 --> 00:30:08.264
Bunch of dumb kids.

431
00:30:08.932 --> 00:30:13.603
Dumb kids doing dumb things.

432
00:30:13.686 --> 00:30:17.398
I know the type.

433
00:30:20.693 --> 00:30:21.820
What now?

434
00:30:24.864 --> 00:30:26.699
We strike up a conversation.

435
00:30:31.287 --> 00:30:32.287
Call.

436
00:30:33.039 --> 00:30:35.166
Two pair. Queens over diamonds.

437
00:30:38.503 --> 00:30:39.587
There they are.

438
00:30:40.588 --> 00:30:42.674
Hello. boys. Am I glad to see you.

439
00:30:43.174 --> 00:30:45.014
We've been looking everywhere
for these horses.

440
00:30:46.469 --> 00:30:49.848
Tell you what. a lot of people owe you
a debt of gratitude for finding 'em.

441
00:30:55.228 --> 00:30:57.772
Everything's fine.
It's time for them to come home.

442
00:31:09.742 --> 00:31:11.286
Hey. whoa.

443
00:31:11.369 --> 00:31:13.788
Hey.

444
00:31:13.872 --> 00:31:16.708
If we go now.
we can march them back by sunset.

445
00:31:18.293 --> 00:31:19.627
I think we should let 'em go.

446
00:31:21.087 --> 00:31:23.756
as long as they agree
not to show their faces here again.

447
00:31:25.466 --> 00:31:26.885
You're making a mistake.

448
00:31:28.219 --> 00:31:30.179
What do you boys think? Is it a mistake?

449
00:31:32.765 --> 00:31:34.125
'Cause I may not be here next time

450
00:31:34.183 --> 00:31:36.269
to stop Lacey from putting a few holes
in your head.

451
00:31:36.352 --> 00:31:37.896
You won't see us again.

452
00:31:38.396 --> 00:31:39.772
Then go on.

453
00:31:49.073 --> 00:31:52.410
-You don't like to fight?
-Nothing good ever comes of it.

454
00:31:54.495 --> 00:31:55.496
I disagree.

455
00:31:58.917 --> 00:32:00.084
Me too.

456
00:32:00.752 --> 00:32:02.211
But you're a good man.

457
00:32:09.010 --> 00:32:10.053
There's my Pet.

458
00:32:11.638 --> 00:32:13.973
-Tell us another. Laura.
-Please. Laura?

459
00:32:14.557 --> 00:32:17.852
Lady Francesca. you shouldn't be listening
to all of this nonsense.

460
00:32:17.936 --> 00:32:19.479
not when the duke is on his way home.

461
00:32:19.562 --> 00:32:22.565
You don't have to listen. Mary.
You can go back to the other room.

462
00:32:28.196 --> 00:32:31.324
Do you wanna hear the story
about how we tried to cross a river

463
00:32:32.075 --> 00:32:34.202
and almost drowned?

464
00:32:34.869 --> 00:32:37.914
Every last one of us. even our dog.

465
00:32:37.997 --> 00:32:39.624
Yes!

466
00:32:40.375 --> 00:32:43.086
Lots of wagons had crossed
before us.

467
00:32:43.169 --> 00:32:46.881
but spring rains
made the river run fast and deep.

468
00:32:47.382 --> 00:32:50.051
Suddenly. the horses
couldn't touch the bottom anymore.

469
00:32:50.134 --> 00:32:53.930
and the current started
pulling all of us downstream.

470
00:32:54.013 --> 00:32:56.349
And if Independence is to grow.

471
00:32:56.432 --> 00:32:59.143
we'll want to establish
strong town traditions

472
00:32:59.227 --> 00:33:01.604
before the railroad lays a single track.

473
00:33:01.688 --> 00:33:03.773
which is why Eli and I have decided

474
00:33:03.856 --> 00:33:07.026
to hold a Founders' Day festival
next summer.

475
00:33:07.110 --> 00:33:08.861
-Fantastic.
-Good idea.

476
00:33:10.738 --> 00:33:12.949
Caroline. I love the enthusiasm.

477
00:33:15.034 --> 00:33:17.370
If we're meant to be a women's society.

478
00:33:17.453 --> 00:33:19.914
shouldn't we include all of the women
of our community.

479
00:33:19.998 --> 00:33:22.166
not just the ones you deem respectable?

480
00:33:24.460 --> 00:33:26.879
Perhaps that's a topic for another time.

481
00:33:28.047 --> 00:33:29.924
Unless anyone disagrees?

482
00:33:38.891 --> 00:33:40.226
Shall we continue?

483
00:33:45.356 --> 00:33:46.816
Thank you for lunch.

484
00:33:51.070 --> 00:33:52.070
Hm.

485
00:33:54.532 --> 00:33:55.867
Caleb. wait!

486
00:33:58.036 --> 00:33:59.454
What are you doing here?

487
00:33:59.954 --> 00:34:03.541
-We came for tea with Edith and Romanzy.
-Oh.

488
00:34:03.624 --> 00:34:05.752
-How's that going?
-They aren't very nice.

489
00:34:06.836 --> 00:34:08.796
Neither of them
have ever said a word to me.

490
00:34:08.880 --> 00:34:11.049
even when I say something first.

491
00:34:11.132 --> 00:34:14.761
or even when I run cookies over after dark
when they feel like having cookies.

492
00:34:16.763 --> 00:34:20.558
-They made it seem like they knew you.
-Why? What did they say?

493
00:34:23.186 --> 00:34:25.396
They said your parents
left you out on the trail.

494
00:34:28.149 --> 00:34:31.402
-That's a lie.
-I'm just telling you what they told me.

495
00:34:31.486 --> 00:34:33.279
Then why would you repeat it?

496
00:34:33.362 --> 00:34:34.362
I'm sorry.

497
00:34:38.951 --> 00:34:42.955
Mary has a boyfriend!
Mary has a boyfriend!

498
00:34:43.039 --> 00:34:46.876
So. it is Caleb.
You do like the ugly orphan boy.

499
00:34:56.177 --> 00:34:58.054
Wait! Caleb!

500
00:35:00.932 --> 00:35:01.932
Girls.

501
00:35:02.433 --> 00:35:04.435
I've been looking everywhere
for you. Let's go.

502
00:35:04.519 --> 00:35:06.479
Say your goodbyes to Edith and Romanzy.

503
00:35:23.538 --> 00:35:25.665
Bye. Laura. Bye. Mary.

504
00:35:27.166 --> 00:35:28.334
What happened. Ma?

505
00:35:29.168 --> 00:35:30.168
What's wrong?

506
00:35:33.714 --> 00:35:35.341
Stay here. Mind yourselves.

507
00:36:09.750 --> 00:36:10.793
I'm sorry.

508
00:36:13.588 --> 00:36:15.131
Jemma is who she is.

509
00:36:16.507 --> 00:36:18.759
It's foolish to expect anything different.

510
00:36:20.052 --> 00:36:21.304
It isn't foolish.

511
00:36:25.099 --> 00:36:28.102
There are battles worth fighting.
and Jemma James isn't one of 'em.

512
00:36:32.064 --> 00:36:33.191
Did you walk out on her?

513
00:36:36.235 --> 00:36:37.570
I guess I did.

514
00:36:55.546 --> 00:36:57.006
-Thank you.
-Mm-hm.

515
00:37:01.344 --> 00:37:02.637
Mm.

516
00:37:14.357 --> 00:37:15.357
Ma!

517
00:37:16.067 --> 00:37:17.693
Ma. it's Pet and Patty!

518
00:37:23.074 --> 00:37:24.742
Like I always say.

519
00:37:24.825 --> 00:37:28.663
peace and justice
make for a well-ordered society.

520
00:37:35.461 --> 00:37:37.171
-Pa. you found them.
-Yeah.

521
00:37:38.130 --> 00:37:39.382
I missed you so much.

522
00:37:39.882 --> 00:37:41.092
They missed you too.

523
00:37:47.974 --> 00:37:49.854
I thought
you were building a church.

524
00:37:49.934 --> 00:37:50.934
I was.

525
00:37:51.435 --> 00:37:53.020
I got sidetracked.

526
00:38:03.155 --> 00:38:04.991
You're welcome. you oaf.

527
00:38:14.333 --> 00:38:17.293
-Bright and early tomorrow?
-We'll get the rest up in no time.

528
00:38:22.133 --> 00:38:23.384
I'm ready to go home.

529
00:38:26.262 --> 00:38:28.431
Just one more stop. I'll be quick.

530
00:38:46.949 --> 00:38:48.492
-Take care.
-Yeah.

531
00:39:10.389 --> 00:39:11.557
Come have dinner with us.

532
00:39:12.558 --> 00:39:13.558
You and Lacey.

533
00:39:17.396 --> 00:39:19.065
The girls miss you terribly.

534
00:39:22.193 --> 00:39:24.612
Nah. I shouldn't let 'em see me like this.

535
00:39:28.074 --> 00:39:29.074
Please come.

536
00:39:59.772 --> 00:40:02.775
-Play another one.
-Oh. I don't know. It's gettin' late.

537
00:40:02.858 --> 00:40:06.487
Please. Mr. Edwards? Thought of you
every day. and now you're finally here.

538
00:40:09.281 --> 00:40:11.534
Well. how about a song
I used to sing for my girls?

539
00:40:12.243 --> 00:40:14.703
"Sweet By-and-By." Know it. Charles?

540
00:40:14.787 --> 00:40:15.787
Hm.

541
00:40:28.926 --> 00:40:32.930
♪ There's a land that is fairer than day ♪

542
00:40:34.640 --> 00:40:39.145
♪ And by faith we can see it afar ♪

543
00:40:40.146 --> 00:40:44.400
♪ For the Father waits over the way ♪

544
00:40:45.484 --> 00:40:48.279
♪ To prepare us a dwell… ♪

545
00:40:48.362 --> 00:40:49.613
Sorry.

546
00:40:51.157 --> 00:40:55.661
♪ In the sweet by-and-by ♪

547
00:40:56.620 --> 00:41:01.167
♪ We shall meet on that beautiful shore ♪

548
00:41:02.334 --> 00:41:06.630
♪ In the sweet by-and-by ♪

549
00:41:07.798 --> 00:41:11.886
♪ We shall meet on that beautiful shore ♪

550
00:41:23.939 --> 00:41:24.939
Another one.

551
00:41:25.274 --> 00:41:26.274
Yes.

552
00:41:52.968 --> 00:41:56.514
At least there was one good thing
about visiting those dumb girls.

552
